8","1224":"1224","21 MAY 1208":"21 mei 1208","1221":"1221","from 1188 to 1197":"van 1188 to 1197","1208":"1208","Tournai, Hainaut, Belgium":"Doornik, Henegouwen, België","Tournai, Hainaut, Belgique":"Doornik, Henegouwen, België"},"en":{"1158–21 MAY 1208":"1158–21 May 1208","1158–1208":"1158–1208","1172–1224":"1172–1224","1185–1221":"1185–1221","1190–1226":"1190–1226","1129–1190":"1129–1190","1129–1197":"1129–1197","1190":"1190","07 Mar 1190":"7 March 1190","1197":"1197","1185":"1185","1172":"1172","1129":"1129","1226":"1226","1158":"1158","1224":"1224","21 MAY 1208":"21 May 1208","1221":"1221","from 1188 to 1197":"from 1188 to 1197","1208":"1208","Tournai, Hainaut, Belgium":"Tournai, Hainaut, Belgium","Tournai, Hainaut, Belgique":"Tournai, Hainaut, Belgium","nameMeanings":[{"name":"DE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"TOURNAI","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Turney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Turney","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","habitational name from any of the places in northern France called Tournai-sur-Dive (Orne), Tournay-sur-Odon (Calvados), or Tourny (Eure), or occasionally from Tournai in Hainaut (Belgium).","perhaps occasionally an occupational name from Middle English <i>tournei</i>, <i>turnai</i> ‘lawyer’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>tourné</i>), or a nickname from Middle English <i>tournei(en)</i> ‘(to) joust, take part in a tournament’ (Old French <i>torneier</i>). Compare   Turner  ."]}]},{"name":"Baudouin","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Baldwin</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Iv","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Vivian   and   Vivien ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]},{"name":"Sire","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pronounced ‘<b>shee</b>-la’; derived in the early Middle Ages from Anglo-Norman <i>Cecile</i>.  See  <b>Cecily</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Shilla","meanings":["Modern coinage, apparently an altered form of   Sheila ."]},{"name":"Sheelah","meanings":["Pronounced ‘<b>shee</b>-la’; derived in the early Middle Ages from Anglo-Norman <i>Cecile</i>.  See  <b>Cecily</b>   ."]},{"name":"Sheila","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of <i>Síle</i>, the Irish Gaelic form of   Cecily .  This name has become so common and widespread that it is hardly felt to be Irish any longer. In Australia since the 19th century it has been a slang generic term for any woman."]},{"name":"Shelagh","meanings":["Variant of   Sheila .  The final consonants in the written form seem to have been added to give a Gaelic feel to the name. There is no etymological justification for them."]},{"name":"Shayla","meanings":["Recent coinage, apparently a variant of   Sheila ."]},{"name":"Sheelagh","meanings":["Pronounced ‘<b>shee</b>-la’; derived in the early Middle Ages from Anglo-Norman <i>Cecile</i>.  See  <b>Cecily</b>   ."]}]},{"name":"De","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mortagne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Francoise, Herve, Marcel, Philippe, Pierre.","French: topographic name for someone who lived on or near a hill, from Old French <i>montaine</i> ‘hill, (small) mountain’; or a habitational name from any of several places called (La) Montagne, named with the same word.","Shortened form of French   Lamontagne  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Mountain","meanings":["English (Yorkshire; of Norman origin): topographic name from Middle English <i>mountaine</i> ‘mountain’ (Old French <i>montagne</i>). See   Montagne  .","Irish: either of Norman origin, as 1 above, or a variant of   Manton  .","English: variant of <b>Monkton</b> a habitational name from Monkton (Kent, Somerset), Moor Monkton and Nun Monkton (Yorkshire), Bishop Monkton (Yorkshire), or any of numerous other places called Monkton, named with Old English <i>munuc</i> ‘monk’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]},{"name":"Lamontagne","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Lucien, Marcel, Emile, Pierre, Aime, Andre, Fernand, Normand, Gaston, Ovide, Achille.","French:","habitational name for someone from any of several places called La Montagne, or a variant of the topographic name   Montagne   1, with fused feminine definite article <i>la</i>."]}]},{"name":"Castellan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian (northeastern): variant of   Castellano  .","Americanized form of Croatian <b>Kaštelan</b> or of its variant <b>Kastelan</b>: occupational name from <i>kaštelan</i> ‘castellan, fortress commander’, also ‘warden of a prison’. Compare   Castelan   2.","French (southern): variant of <b>Castella</b>, a southern variant of <b>Châtelain</b> ‘lord (of the manor)’; see   Chatelain  . In part, it is probably of Italian origin (see   Castellano  , compare 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Castellano","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Miguel, Enrique, Armando, Carlos, Roberto, Guadalupe, Jesus, Luis, Manuel, Ruben.  Italian Carmine, Rocco, Angelo, Salvatore, Vito, Antonio, Carmela, Cosmo, Battista, Carlo, Dario, Enrico.","Spanish: habitational or ethnic name for someone from Castile.","Italian: habitational name for someone from any of the places called Castello, or a topographic name from <i>castellano</i> (from Latin <i>castellanus</i>), denoting someone who lived or worked in a castle. Compare   Castello  ."]},{"name":"Castelan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Miguel, Francisco, Alejandro, Guadalupe, Concepcion, Felipe, Gerardo, Jorge, Jose Luis, Manuel, Serafin.","Galician (<b>Castelán</b>): generally from Galician <i>castelán</i>, the ethnic name for a Castilian (Castilian <i>castellano</i>). However, in some cases it may be a habitational name from any of the places in Lugo and A Coruña provinces, Spain, called Castelán, or it could be an occupational name denoting a bailiff or steward.","In some cases also an Americanized form of Croatian <b>Kaštelan</b> (see   Castellan   2)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Baudouin Iv Sire De Mortagne Castellan DE TOURNAI was born in 1158, in Tournai, Hainaut, Belgium, his father, Everard III Ralph de Mortagne, was 29 and his mother, Gertrude de Lorraine de flandres, was 29. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Hildegarde de Wavrin. He died on 21 May 1208, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1158–21 MAY 1208":"1158–21. mai 1208","1158–1208":"1158–1208","1172–1224":"1172–1224","1185–1221":"1185–1221","1190–1226":"1190–1226","1129–1190":"1129–1190","1129–1197":"1129–1197","1190":"1190","07 Mar 1190":"7. märts 1190","1197":"1197","1185":"1185","1172":"1172","1129":"1129","1226":"1226","1158":"1158","1224":"1224","21 MAY 1208":"21. mai 1208","1221":"1221","from 1188 to 1197":"1188 kuni 1197","1208":"1208","Tournai, Hainaut, Belgium":"Tournai, Hainaut, Belgia","Tournai, Hainaut, Belgique":"Tournai, Hainaut, Belgia"},"fi":{"1158–21 MAY 1208":"1158–21. toukokuuta 1208","1158–1208":"1158–1208","1172–1224":"1172–1224","1185–1221":"1185–1221","1190–1226":"1190–1226","1129–1190":"1129–1190","1129–1197":"1129–1197","1190":"1190","07 Mar 1190":"7. maaliskuuta 1190","1197":"1197","1185":"1185","1172":"1172","1129":"1129","1226":"1226","1158":"1158","1224":"1224","21 MAY 1208":"21. toukokuuta 1208","1221":"1221","from 1188 to 1197":"vuodesta 1188 vuoteen 1197","1208":"1208","Tournai, Hainaut, Belgium":"Tournai, Hainaut, Belgia","Tournai, Hainaut, Belgique":"Tournai, Hainaut, Belgia"},"fr":{"1158–21 MAY 1208":"1158–21 mai 1208","1158–1208":"1158–1208","1172–1224":"1172–1224","1185–1221":"1185–1221","1190–1226":"1190–1226","1129–1190":"1129–1190","1129–1197":"1129–1197","1190":"1190","07 Mar 1190":"7 mars 1190","1197":"1197","1185":"1185","1172":"1172","1129":"1129","1226":"1226","1158":"1158","1224":"1224","21 MAY 1208":"21 mai 1208","1221":"1221","from 1188 to 1197":"du 1188 au 1197","1208":"1208","Tournai, Hainaut, Belgium":"Tournai,